00:14:20,322 --> 00:14:23,655
<i>[Manson] I had a hard time doing</i>
<i>the swim test back in California.</i>

200
00:14:24,993 --> 00:14:27,154
<i>I was very nervous.</i>

201
00:14:32,034 --> 00:14:34,264
- [man] Keep coming.
- [man 2] Almost there.

202
00:14:34,303 --> 00:14:35,895
[man] You're almost there.

203
00:14:47,449 --> 00:14:49,940
- [breathing heavily]
- [man] You're almost there.

204
00:14:49,985 --> 00:14:51,680
Help him, help him.

205
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:56,123
OK, guys. Out of the pool.
Nice job, everybody.

206
00:14:56,158 --> 00:14:57,989
[applause]

207
00:15:07,669 --> 00:15:11,332
<i>[Manson] It is really emotional for me.</i>
<i>My mother passed recently.</i>

208
00:15:11,373 --> 00:15:14,274
<i>She passed in February this year.</i>

209
00:15:14,309 --> 00:15:16,573
[Kirby] You're gonna go home
to Baltimore.

210
00:15:16,612 --> 00:15:18,136
You're gonna learn how to swim

211
00:15:18,180 --> 00:15:20,444
'cause when you get to Hawaii,
you better be ready...

212
00:15:20,482 --> 00:15:21,506
Holy...

213
00:15:21,550 --> 00:15:25,646
- [laughter]
- Oh, my God! Oh, my God.

214
00:15:27,122 --> 00:15:29,818
- Are you serious?
- [Kirby] I'm serious. Very serious.

215
00:15:29,858 --> 00:15:31,849
Oh, my God. Oh...

216
00:15:31,894 --> 00:15:34,590
<i>[Manson] First thing I thought of</i>
<i>was my mother.</i>

217
00:15:34,630 --> 00:15:40,432
I don't know. I just know
she's proud of me, man.

218
00:15:46,441 --> 00:15:48,306
Ah...

219
00:15:48,343 --> 00:15:52,712
<i>[Manson] You only get</i>
<i>certain opportunities in life,</i>

220
00:15:52,748 --> 00:15:57,412
<i>and if you don't hop on 'em,</i>
<i>they'll go like that.</i>

221
00:15:57,452 --> 00:15:59,886
<i>I live with my sister,</i>
<i>and my nieces and nephews.</i>

222
00:15:59,922 --> 00:16:02,618
<i>I don't even grasp the whole concept of,</i>
<i>you know, like,</i>

223
00:16:02,658 --> 00:16:04,023
<i>sailing through the ocean,</i>

224
00:16:04,059 --> 00:16:07,051
<i>and I'm quite sure that</i>
<i>they probably don't either.</i>

225
00:16:07,095 --> 00:16:09,791
<i>I think they do have, somewhat,</i>
<i>a fear for me, you know.</i>

226
00:16:09,831 --> 00:16:12,698
Could be a chance that, you
know, I might not make it back.

227
00:16:16,972 --> 00:16:20,601
So what we're gonna do is, we're gonna
sail upwind, we're gonna set a kite.

228
00:16:20,642 --> 00:16:24,169
We're gonna have six people on deck. The
rest are gonna be down in your bunks,

229
00:16:24,212 --> 00:16:27,613
and we're gonna simulate
a man overboard with a kite up.

230
00:16:28,517 --> 00:16:31,714
Steve's gonna jump over the side.
He very nicely volunteered.

231
00:16:33,288 --> 00:16:35,222
[laughing]

232
00:16:35,257 --> 00:16:39,193
<i>[man] January 21st.</i>
<i>I think the best way to overcome fear</i>

233
00:16:39,227 --> 00:16:40,785
<i>is to face it head-on.</i>

234
00:16:50,372 --> 00:16:52,306
[Haines] Anytime, Steve.

235
00:16:52,341 --> 00:16:54,002
Go, buddy.

236
00:16:55,043 --> 00:16:57,739
- [man] Help!
- [Tulloch] Man overboard!

237
00:16:58,580 --> 00:17:01,606
[Tulloch] Pointing, pointing.
Got him. Got him.

238
00:17:01,650 --> 00:17:04,448
Pull him along, right?
I got him.

239
00:17:04,486 --> 00:17:06,716
- [Haines] Don't look back.
- [Tulloch] Still have him?

240
00:17:06,755 --> 00:17:09,690
<i>[Manson] You hit the water,</i>
<i>it takes five seconds to come up.</i>

241
00:17:09,725 --> 00:17:12,285
<i>Then you see the boat,</i>
<i>and it's like a half a mile away.</i>

242
00:17:12,327 --> 00:17:13,851
[Haines]
OK, kite down.

243
00:17:13,895 --> 00:17:16,193
<i>[Wilmot] In good breeze,</i>
<i>every second counts,</i>

244
00:17:16,231 --> 00:17:19,428
<i>especially when you're hauling ass</i>
<i>doing 18 knots with the kite up.</i>

245
00:17:19,468 --> 00:17:21,527
[Haines]
Wait. What are you doing?

246
00:17:21,570 --> 00:17:23,834
<i>[Wilmot] It's not like you can</i>
<i>pull the hand brake</i>

247
00:17:23,872 --> 00:17:25,305
<i>and spin the boat on a dime.</i>

248
00:17:27,376 --> 00:17:29,241
[overlapping chatter]

249
00:17:33,315 --> 00:17:35,215
[man] OK, gotcha.

250
00:17:35,250 --> 00:17:37,218
[Tulloch] Hold on, hold on.
You need...

251
00:17:37,252 --> 00:17:39,413
[Haines] Come on, guys. Main in.

252
00:17:39,454 --> 00:17:42,355
- [Haines] He's out of sight.
- I got ya. He's right here.

253
00:17:47,295 --> 00:17:50,025
Come on. Turn!

254
00:17:50,065 --> 00:17:52,499
Here it comes!

255
00:17:52,534 --> 00:17:55,526
[Tulloch] All right, two big guys,
we're gonna pick him up.

256
00:17:57,239 --> 00:17:59,469
Off our bow.

257
00:18:05,947 --> 00:18:08,142
- Throw him a line!
- Gotta be long.

258
00:18:12,654 --> 00:18:15,919
[overlapping chatter]

259
00:18:15,957 --> 00:18:17,720
[cheering, whooping]

260
00:18:17,759 --> 00:18:20,626
- [Brant-Zawadzki] Welcome back, man.
- [Haines] Good job!

261
00:18:20,662 --> 00:18:22,789
- Yeah!
- [overlapping chatter]

262
00:18:22,831 --> 00:18:24,799
- [laugh]
- <i>[Fielding] All I remember</i>

263
00:18:24,833 --> 00:18:27,324
<i>is feeling a sense of</i>
<i>accomplishment as a group</i>

264
00:18:27,369 --> 00:18:29,599
<i>that we got Steve back on that boat,</i>

265
00:18:29,638 --> 00:18:32,038
<i>and that he had conquered</i>
<i>a big hurdle in his life.</i>

266
00:18:37,079 --> 00:18:40,913
<i>In a real race,</i>
<i>at night, in bad weather,</i>

267
00:18:40,949 --> 00:18:45,010
<i>that training exercise</i>
<i>will always be in the back of my head.</i>

268
00:18:46,421 --> 00:18:48,889
[Will] I thought we got back there
pretty quickly.

269
00:18:48,924 --> 00:18:51,017
Definitely, like,
you realize how quickly

270
00:18:51,059 --> 00:18:52,993
you get away from somebody
with a chute up.

271
00:18:53,028 --> 00:18:56,464
So, you were pointin' at the ring,
right? But she still couldn't see me?

272
00:18:56,498 --> 00:18:59,797
I mean, I could see a little bit
of fleck on the top of a wave.

273
00:18:59,835 --> 00:19:01,393
But you went out of sight,

274
00:19:01,436 --> 00:19:03,631
- I wanna say a minute. Not even.
- Wow.

275
00:19:03,672 --> 00:19:08,234
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] We're a team of 15.</i>
<i>Every single person deserves to race.</i>

276
00:19:08,276 --> 00:19:10,301
<i>We can't all go. Only 11.</i>

277
00:19:10,345 --> 00:19:15,248
<i>[man] We as a team will be picking</i>
<i>the four who stay behind.</i>

278
00:19:15,283 --> 00:19:20,380
<i>As the youngest team member, this has</i>
<i>been extremely nerve-racking for me.</i>

279
00:19:24,359 --> 00:19:25,656
Bring me back in, Chris.

280
00:19:25,694 --> 00:19:29,687
Guys, I'd like to practice
some jibes, if we got the time.

281
00:19:29,731 --> 00:19:32,894
- [Kane] Let's pre-check.
- [Fielding] We're gonna go real slow.

282
00:19:32,934 --> 00:19:36,028
All right, clear to jibe.
Jibing.

283
00:19:36,071 --> 00:19:40,508
<i>[Honey] Jibes are the turns that you</i>
<i>have to do in order to get downwind,</i>

284
00:19:40,542 --> 00:19:43,170
<i>because the boat can't sail</i>
<i>directly downwind.</i>

285
00:19:43,211 --> 00:19:45,907
<i>So instead you sail</i>
<i>40 degrees one way,</i>

286
00:19:45,947 --> 00:19:51,579
<i>turn, or you jibe, and then you sail 40</i>
<i>degrees off the wind the other way.</i>

287
00:19:51,620 --> 00:19:52,712
<i>Tacks are similar.</i>

288
00:19:52,754 --> 00:19:55,780
<i>Tacks are the turns that you have to do</i>
<i>when you're going upwind.</i>

289
00:19:55,824 --> 00:19:58,384
[Fielding] OK, we're sailing again.

290
00:19:58,426 --> 00:20:02,157
[Kirby] Sailing's always been
a complex sport. It's not that simple.

291
00:20:02,197 --> 00:20:04,688
I mean, you could
stay in it for a lifetime

292
00:20:04,733 --> 00:20:08,794
and never have it completely
figured out or perfected.

293
00:20:08,837 --> 00:20:11,704
What is that?
Push it a little!

294
00:20:13,542 --> 00:20:15,476
Little bit too wimpy.

295
00:20:15,510 --> 00:20:18,206
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki]</i>
<i>P.S., whoever said big boats are</i>

296
00:20:18,246 --> 00:20:21,181
<i>just like dinghies is full of it.</i>

297
00:20:21,216 --> 00:20:25,380
<i>Screwups, kites in the water,</i>
<i>kites exploding.</i>

298
00:20:25,420 --> 00:20:28,548
<i>We need to sort</i>
<i>these issues out ourselves</i>

299
00:20:28,590 --> 00:20:31,024
<i>and learn to deal with them</i>
<i>before this race begins.</i>

300
00:20:31,059 --> 00:20:33,118
- Oops!
- Don't tear it!

301
00:20:33,161 --> 00:20:36,494
Without a team being totally focused
in one positive direction,

302
00:20:36,531 --> 00:20:38,192
you're not gonna be successful.

303
00:20:38,233 --> 00:20:40,133
First aid kit? Stocked.

304
00:20:40,168 --> 00:20:42,602
Paper towels? Check.
Toilet paper? Check.

305
00:20:42,637 --> 00:20:44,764
Coffee? Check. Soap?

306
00:20:46,274 --> 00:20:49,175
Just make darn sure
we've got enough life jackets.

307
00:20:49,211 --> 00:20:53,443
We wanted the kids to be very familiar
with finishing a Transpac race.

308
00:20:53,481 --> 00:20:56,450
So we had them sail over to Molokai,

309
00:20:56,484 --> 00:20:59,920
down the Molokai Channel
and then come into Diamond Head.

310
00:20:59,955 --> 00:21:02,981
[man] OK. Let's go. You guys ready?

311
00:21:03,024 --> 00:21:06,983
We had sent them off overnight
by themselves completely.

312
00:21:07,028 --> 00:21:09,588
[wind howling]

313
00:21:13,301 --> 00:21:16,293
[Wilmot] Let's finish this race up
and get outta here!

314
00:21:16,338 --> 00:21:19,102
[overlapping shouts]

315
00:21:19,140 --> 00:21:22,769
[overlapping chatter]

316
00:21:23,378 --> 00:21:25,403
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] My first overnight.</i>

317
00:21:26,848 --> 00:21:30,944
<i>It was scary, wet, there was</i>
<i>a lot of awkward flailing,</i>

318
00:21:30,986 --> 00:21:34,149
<i>and I passed out</i>
<i>before we finished.</i>

319
00:21:35,924 --> 00:21:38,825
<i>A few other kids just</i>
<i>puked the whole time.</i>

320
00:21:40,161 --> 00:21:42,595
<i>That trip seriously</i>
<i>took it out of the whole team,</i>

321
00:21:42,631 --> 00:21:45,065
<i>and that was just</i>
<i>over 24 hours.</i>

322
00:21:45,100 --> 00:21:48,729
<i>We were sloppy</i>
<i>and out of shape.</i>

323
00:21:48,770 --> 00:21:52,228
<i>[Honey] They'd show up with the boat</i>
<i>trashed. You know, everything a mess.</i>

324
00:21:52,274 --> 00:21:55,801
They hadn't really taken on, you know,
this offshore seamanship.

325
00:21:55,844 --> 00:21:57,835
And they weren't
in any kind of condition

326
00:21:57,879 --> 00:22:00,279
to be able to continue sailing
the way you have to

327
00:22:00,315 --> 00:22:03,478
- when you cross an ocean.
- [snoring]

328
00:22:03,518 --> 00:22:06,578
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] At the current pace</i>
<i>we will not be ready.</i>

329
00:22:06,621 --> 00:22:08,179
[snoring]

330
00:22:08,223 --> 00:22:11,420
<i>We're beginning to realize</i>
<i>the need to push ourselves harder.</i>

331
00:22:11,459 --> 00:22:14,155
If we're gonna have these coaches,
let's not waste them.

332
00:22:14,195 --> 00:22:16,026
Let's use them to their full...

333
00:22:16,064 --> 00:22:17,827
Even if you think it's obvious.

334
00:22:17,866 --> 00:22:20,460
It could be something
that's obvious, but...

335
00:22:20,502 --> 00:22:23,335
...half of us wouldn't know,
the people that do don't care.

336
00:22:23,371 --> 00:22:25,066
The best thing is...

337
00:22:25,106 --> 00:22:29,634
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] Everything hinges</i>
<i>on the skipper and the leader.</i>

338
00:22:29,678 --> 00:22:32,647
<i>On an hourly basis, they will decide</i>
<i>our fate on the</i> Morning Light.

339
00:22:32,681 --> 00:22:35,479
I want to say one thing for, um, Genny.

340
00:22:35,517 --> 00:22:39,078
'Cause there's been a lot of times
where we've been hanging out as a group,

341
00:22:39,120 --> 00:22:41,987
and if Genny says,
"Hey, we need to be there now,"

342
00:22:42,023 --> 00:22:44,548
everyone's like, picks up
their bags and we go.

343
00:22:44,592 --> 00:22:48,619
Her organization definitely keeps us all
together. I definitely agree with that.

344
00:22:48,663 --> 00:22:51,655
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] The way to get good</i>
<i>at making those decisions</i>

345
00:22:51,700 --> 00:22:52,826
<i>is to be placed in them.</i>

346
00:22:52,867 --> 00:22:56,394
[man] Who's gonna go in to shore?
Are we ready?

347
00:22:56,438 --> 00:23:00,306
Yeah. I got it blowing.
Blow it! Yeah!

348
00:23:03,078 --> 00:23:06,047
Mike Sanderson, who just won
the around-the-world race,

349
00:23:06,081 --> 00:23:08,572
he came in for a week to train the kids.

350
00:23:08,616 --> 00:23:11,141
<i>[Tulloch] The second that Moose</i>
<i>stepped on the boat,</i>

351
00:23:11,186 --> 00:23:12,949
<i>we realized how unprepared we were,</i>

352
00:23:12,988 --> 00:23:15,752
<i>how much we had to learn,</i>
<i>and how much he could teach us.</i>

353
00:23:15,790 --> 00:23:18,384
Faster, faster, faster,
faster, faster. Let it go.

354
00:23:22,864 --> 00:23:26,766
They're not rock stars yet. You know,
they're not professional sailors.

355
00:23:26,801 --> 00:23:27,961
[Schubert] Pull back.

356
00:23:28,003 --> 00:23:31,598
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] We need to prove to</i>
<i>ourselves that we can sail this boat.</i>

357
00:23:31,639 --> 00:23:34,665
[Schubert] You're controlling the thing.
You call, all right?

358
00:23:34,709 --> 00:23:37,542
One minute, Towiller,
keep talking to me.

359
00:23:37,579 --> 00:23:40,776
[Sanderson]
Yeah, and smoke it. Smoke it.

360
00:23:40,815 --> 00:23:42,942
Nice one.
Basic dilemma. Yeah, baby.

361
00:23:42,984 --> 00:23:46,385
Keep coming, keep coming, keep coming,
keep coming, keep coming.

362
00:23:47,022 --> 00:23:48,046
Go, Jeremy.

363
00:23:50,959 --> 00:23:52,927
<i>[Branning] I had never been</i>
<i>part of a team</i>

364
00:23:52,961 --> 00:23:54,861
<i>that wants it more than</i> Morning Light.

365
00:23:55,497 --> 00:23:59,866
<i>I've raced in five countries,</i>
<i>endless practices on all types of boats</i>

366
00:24:01,403 --> 00:24:04,634
<i>and this was my favorite day</i>
<i>of sailing I've ever had.</i>

367
00:24:21,423 --> 00:24:24,290
<i>[Tulloch] I wish, at least,</i>
<i>it was a good story.</i>

368
00:24:24,325 --> 00:24:27,351
<i>I wish I could say I'd jumped</i>
<i>off a cliff into the shallows</i>

369
00:24:28,129 --> 00:24:30,757
<i>or was attacked by a shark</i>
<i>while kite-surfing.</i>

370
00:24:30,799 --> 00:24:33,996
<i>Something really fun and off-the-wall.</i>

371
00:24:35,837 --> 00:24:39,830
She didn't take our advice. She went off
snowboarding between sessions.

372
00:24:39,874 --> 00:24:41,933
I said, "You sure
you wanna do that, Genny?"

373
00:24:41,976 --> 00:24:45,139
And she said, "Oh, don't worry,
Robbie. I'll be fine."

374
00:24:48,883 --> 00:24:51,147
<i>[Tulloch] I sat down and cried.</i>

375
00:24:51,186 --> 00:24:53,347
<i>All I knew was that it hurt,</i>

376
00:24:53,388 --> 00:24:58,655
<i>and the major implications</i>
<i>of having broken myself.</i>

377
00:24:58,693 --> 00:25:01,457
[Haines] We wanted the kids
to go offshore for three days.

378
00:25:01,496 --> 00:25:03,964
Then they would meet us in Hilo.

379
00:25:03,998 --> 00:25:08,094
She wanted to participate
a lot more than we allowed her to.

380
00:25:08,136 --> 00:25:10,434
In fact, we didn't allow her
to do anything.

381
00:25:13,775 --> 00:25:15,402
Good luck!

382
00:25:15,443 --> 00:25:17,673
<i>[Tulloch] Disappointment.</i>

383
00:25:17,712 --> 00:25:19,907
<i>Frustration. Loneliness.</i>

384
00:25:19,948 --> 00:25:22,917
- [Tulloch] Bye, guys!
- [man] Bye!

385
00:25:33,161 --> 00:25:37,097
<i>[Wilmot] We are now at the stage where</i>
<i>we can sail 24-hour overnight sprints.</i>

386
00:25:37,132 --> 00:25:41,364
<i>However, our race</i>
<i>can be up to ten days long.</i>

387
00:25:41,402 --> 00:25:43,802
<i>The Hilo trip will help us</i>
<i>get into a rhythm</i>

388
00:25:43,838 --> 00:25:46,705
<i>of racing at sea</i>
<i>for several days at a time.</i>

389
00:25:53,781 --> 00:25:55,305
<i>[Kane] Everyone gets seasick.</i>

390
00:25:55,350 --> 00:25:58,342
<i>I don't care if you've sailed</i>
<i>around the world, everyone does.</i>

391
00:25:58,386 --> 00:26:02,755
<i>You're just so uncomfortable.</i>
<i>Your bones ache, you can't think,</i>

392
00:26:02,790 --> 00:26:04,348
<i>you wanna just die.</i>

393
00:26:04,392 --> 00:26:05,950
- [crashing]
- Ah!

394
00:26:05,994 --> 00:26:07,621
I'm gonna give you...

395
00:26:07,662 --> 00:26:09,823
<i>[Branning] Down below it's hot,</i>

396
00:26:09,864 --> 00:26:12,856
<i>it's humid, it's wet, it smells.</i>

397
00:26:12,901 --> 00:26:15,665
<i>For a navigator who's trying</i>
<i>to stare at a computer,</i>

398
00:26:15,703 --> 00:26:17,364
<i>and you're banging in the waves,</i>

399
00:26:17,405 --> 00:26:21,239
<i>I don't care how tough you are,</i>
<i>you're gonna get sick.</i>

400
00:26:21,276 --> 00:26:23,938
[retching]

401
00:26:27,782 --> 00:26:30,080
<i>[Fielding] We kept the boat</i>
<i>in solid condition</i>

402
00:26:30,118 --> 00:26:32,814
<i>throughout three days</i>
<i>of extreme upwind sailing.</i>

403
00:26:33,888 --> 00:26:36,686
<i>My stress level was at an all-time high.</i>

404
00:26:36,724 --> 00:26:39,090
