00:38:43,150 --> 00:38:47,086
I think Kit deserved it.
And he's an awesome sailor, so...

609
00:38:47,121 --> 00:38:49,146
You guys are better off with him.

610
00:38:50,591 --> 00:38:52,491
[Wilmot] That was why we chose you, man.

611
00:38:52,526 --> 00:38:54,357
You're an amazing team player.

612
00:38:55,930 --> 00:38:58,160
- [chuckles]
- [Tulloch] We're gonna miss you.

613
00:39:01,468 --> 00:39:04,596
It's like breaking up
with your girlfriend.

614
00:39:04,638 --> 00:39:07,129
I know. I'm waiting for
the slap... [chuckles]

615
00:39:09,877 --> 00:39:12,607
Graham's a bit more tasteful
than the girls I go out with.

616
00:39:12,646 --> 00:39:15,114
- [laughter]
- [Brant-Zawadzki] That's for sure.

617
00:39:18,218 --> 00:39:22,052
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] We had come to the end</i>
<i>of a long, intense six months.</i>

618
00:39:22,089 --> 00:39:24,990
<i>The night before the race,</i>
<i>we got a really nice surprise.</i>

619
00:39:25,826 --> 00:39:27,987
- Dim the lights.
- [laughter]

620
00:39:28,028 --> 00:39:30,394
- <i>[whoops]</i>
- [laughing]

621
00:39:32,533 --> 00:39:35,297
- [man] Very cool.
- [man 2] That's awesome.

622
00:39:35,336 --> 00:39:39,204
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] I think everyone was on</i>
<i>edge in terms of anticipation.</i>

623
00:39:39,239 --> 00:39:41,173
<i>There was a lot</i>
<i>of energy in the room.</i>

624
00:39:41,208 --> 00:39:43,574
- [laughter]
- <i>[cheering and whooping]</i>

625
00:39:50,884 --> 00:39:52,010
Oh, my God!

626
00:40:01,996 --> 00:40:03,020
Ah!

627
00:40:03,063 --> 00:40:04,724
Yeah!

628
00:40:07,668 --> 00:40:11,502
<i>[woman] Mark,</i>
<i>we're so very, very proud of you.</i>

629
00:40:11,538 --> 00:40:14,905
<i>We always knew that you would be</i>
<i>sailing home one day.</i>

630
00:40:14,942 --> 00:40:17,570
<i>Good luck, and enjoy the ride.</i>

631
00:40:17,611 --> 00:40:20,546
<i>Genny girl, there have been Tullochs</i>
<i>on the Pacific Ocean before.</i>

632
00:40:20,581 --> 00:40:23,675
<i>Your grandfather sailed</i>
<i>square riggers there</i>

633
00:40:23,717 --> 00:40:26,049
<i>more than 150 years ago.</i>

634
00:40:26,086 --> 00:40:30,580
<i>And now it's another Tulloch crossing</i>
<i>the Pacific Ocean, this time on a race.</i>

635
00:40:30,624 --> 00:40:33,957
<i>We hope you have fun.</i>
<i>We hope you make lots of friends.</i>

636
00:40:33,994 --> 00:40:36,963
<i>And make sure you don't hit</i>
<i>any whales on the way over.</i>

637
00:40:36,997 --> 00:40:38,157
<i>Take care and good luck.</i>

638
00:40:38,198 --> 00:40:40,564
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] Everyone</i>
<i>was happy to hear from their families.</i>

639
00:40:40,601 --> 00:40:42,466
- <i>[woman] Hi, Christopher.</i>
- Oh, Mom.

640
00:40:42,503 --> 00:40:44,471
<i>I'm very happy</i>
<i>and excited for you...</i>

641
00:40:44,505 --> 00:40:46,769
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki]</i>
<i>They are the root of who we are.</i>

642
00:40:46,807 --> 00:40:49,173
<i>We love you from</i>
<i>the bottom of our hearts.</i>

643
00:40:49,209 --> 00:40:51,643
<i>And, as your father would say,</i>

644
00:40:51,678 --> 00:40:55,045
<i>sail fast and stay on course.</i>

645
00:40:55,082 --> 00:40:58,245
<i>Well, Robbie,</i>
<i>beyond "good luck," be careful.</i>

646
00:40:58,285 --> 00:41:00,685
<i>Uh, like any parent, re...</i>
<i>be real careful.</i>

647
00:41:00,721 --> 00:41:04,088
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] There was a common</i>
<i>message of being safe, sailing fast,</i>

648
00:41:04,124 --> 00:41:06,558
<i>and giving it all we can.</i>

649
00:41:06,593 --> 00:41:08,424
<i>Enjoy every minute of it.</i>

650
00:41:08,462 --> 00:41:11,431
<i>And, uh, just give 'em hell.</i>

651
00:41:11,465 --> 00:41:14,730
<i>Jesse MacGowan Baker</i>
<i>Ferguson Fielding... [chuckles]</i>

652
00:41:14,768 --> 00:41:18,431
<i>... you and your mom were so close,</i>
<i>you shared a birthday.</i>

653
00:41:18,472 --> 00:41:20,030
<i>And you had one more birthday...</i>

654
00:41:20,074 --> 00:41:22,907
<i>[Fielding] It was reassuring.</i>
<i>But I don't need a reminder</i>

655
00:41:22,943 --> 00:41:24,968
<i>that my mom is with me on a daily basis.</i>

656
00:41:26,947 --> 00:41:28,574
<i>She wrote to you:</i>

657
00:41:28,615 --> 00:41:31,982
<i>"Think you can, believe you can,</i>

658
00:41:32,019 --> 00:41:33,748
<i>and you will.</i>

659
00:41:33,787 --> 00:41:36,688
<i>Your mother. September '97. "

660
00:41:37,958 --> 00:41:40,654
<i>[Fielding] I don't normally like to</i>
<i>share that side with people...</i>

661
00:41:43,030 --> 00:41:44,725
<i>... but in this case it felt right.</i>

662
00:41:44,765 --> 00:41:47,666
<i>Good luck, Jesse.</i>
<i>Uh, I hope you have a good time</i>

663
00:41:47,701 --> 00:41:50,727
<i>and that you ask 'em</i>
<i>if I should get a haircut.</i>

664
00:41:52,773 --> 00:41:54,798
- <i>[laughs]</i>
- [laughter]

665
00:41:54,842 --> 00:41:56,969
<i>I'll see you when you get there.</i>

666
00:41:57,010 --> 00:42:00,377
<i>Hope you have some good stories.</i>
<i>Uh... good luck.</i>

667
00:42:08,122 --> 00:42:10,955
<i>[man] Now leaving</i>
<i>Rainbow Harbor:</i> Skylark,

668
00:42:10,991 --> 00:42:14,427
<i>the Santa Cruz 70 out of</i>
<i>Newport Beach, California.</i>

669
00:42:14,461 --> 00:42:18,420
<i>Godspeed,</i> Skylark.
<i>And aloha!</i>

670
00:42:18,465 --> 00:42:22,834
<i>That dock was crawling with guys</i>
<i>we've all read about or heard about.</i>

671
00:42:22,870 --> 00:42:24,838
<i>It's like getting</i>
<i>to hit a bucket of balls</i>

672
00:42:24,872 --> 00:42:26,965
<i>on the same driving range</i>
<i>as Tiger Woods.</i>

673
00:42:28,342 --> 00:42:30,708
<i>We've had our sights set</i>
<i>on trying to beat</i> Samba.

674
00:42:30,744 --> 00:42:33,235
- <i>But we are the underdogs.</i>
- [cheering]

675
00:42:33,280 --> 00:42:36,306
<i>[man] Next boat leaving,</i>
Samba Pa Ti.

676
00:42:36,350 --> 00:42:37,908
[cheering and whistling]

677
00:42:41,355 --> 00:42:45,382
<i>[Kane] I'm sick of practicing</i>
<i>and preparing. I'm chomping at the bit.</i>

678
00:42:45,425 --> 00:42:47,916
<i>Hawaii's closer than we think,</i>
<i>so it'll be important</i>

679
00:42:47,961 --> 00:42:49,519
<i>to push 100 percent all the time.</i>

680
00:42:49,563 --> 00:42:51,588
OK, Chris.
Thanks for your help.

681
00:42:51,632 --> 00:42:54,863
[chanting in Hawaiian]

682
00:42:56,270 --> 00:42:57,862
- We'll wait for you.
- Can I have a hug?

683
00:42:57,905 --> 00:42:59,429
- Ahh!
- Bring it in.

684
00:43:00,707 --> 00:43:02,937
- All right.
- [laughter]

685
00:43:08,048 --> 00:43:09,413
[Towill] Let's do this.

686
00:43:12,719 --> 00:43:15,882
[man] Next up, a boat you've been
reading about just a little bit,

687
00:43:15,923 --> 00:43:18,084
- <i>Morning Light!</i>
- [cheering and whistling]

688
00:43:20,661 --> 00:43:22,561
[boy] Go! Yay!

689
00:43:22,596 --> 00:43:27,226
Godspeed, <i>Morning Light.</i>
And aloha!

690
00:43:28,735 --> 00:43:31,169
<i>[Towill] It's pretty powerful</i>
<i>to realize this boat</i>

691
00:43:31,205 --> 00:43:33,765
<i>is the center of the earth</i>
<i>for us, and now this is home.</i>

692
00:43:33,807 --> 00:43:38,267
<i>These, uh, crew members, they're</i>
<i>everything, you know. Everything.</i>

693
00:43:43,817 --> 00:43:45,512
<i>[man] Attention, Transpac racers.</i>

694
00:43:45,552 --> 00:43:48,521
- <i>Five minutes to the start.</i>
- [Branning] Got it. Five minutes.

695
00:43:52,426 --> 00:43:54,894
OK, why don't you go down
below. Kit, you're up.

696
00:43:54,928 --> 00:43:56,418
[Will] Want me to grind?
You want me to grind?

697
00:43:56,463 --> 00:43:58,260
- [Wilmot] Nah.
- [Will] All right.

698
00:43:58,298 --> 00:44:01,461
- How long?
- Two-twenty.

699
00:44:08,709 --> 00:44:12,236
- One-twenty.
- <i>[man] Twenty seconds to P flag down.</i>

700
00:44:12,279 --> 00:44:13,974
[Tulloch] Are we starting on port?

701
00:44:16,717 --> 00:44:18,309
- One minute!
- [indistinct]

702
00:44:19,720 --> 00:44:21,654
- Don't worry, guys.
- [Branning] Forty seconds.

703
00:44:21,688 --> 00:44:24,248
[Will] A little pressure here.
A little pressure.

704
00:44:24,291 --> 00:44:25,656
[Branning] Twenty-five seconds.

705
00:44:28,996 --> 00:44:30,793
[Kane] Holding on the line.

706
00:44:30,831 --> 00:44:32,526
- [Wilmot] Get it set.
- Line, Robbie!

707
00:44:33,700 --> 00:44:35,600
- Ten!
- <i>[man] Nine.</i>

708
00:44:35,636 --> 00:44:38,298
- Get it up now.
- Eight, seven, six...

709
00:44:38,338 --> 00:44:40,329
...five...
- <i>[man]... four...</i>

710
00:44:40,374 --> 00:44:43,366
...three, two, one!

711
00:44:43,410 --> 00:44:44,843
<i>[man] Now.</i>

712
00:44:47,948 --> 00:44:49,313
[Wilmot] Medium down.

713
00:44:52,152 --> 00:44:53,847
- Whoo-hoo!
- Whoo!

714
00:44:53,887 --> 00:44:55,980
[Kane] Hey! Yes!

715
00:45:01,828 --> 00:45:03,728
[Sanderson] I remember it
being very adventurous,

716
00:45:03,764 --> 00:45:05,959
- the first time I crossed an ocean.
- Come on, Towiller.

717
00:45:05,999 --> 00:45:09,935
These guys, they're getting to grow
and learn at a very similar age group.

718
00:45:09,970 --> 00:45:13,064
That's a fantastic opportunity,
and I wish something like this

719
00:45:13,106 --> 00:45:15,301
had popped up for me when I was 21.

720
00:45:15,342 --> 00:45:18,470
<i>[#</i> Gay Dad: <i>To Earth With Love]</i>

721
00:45:34,027 --> 00:45:38,657
- Well, here we are at Transpac 2007.
- Yeah!

722
00:45:38,699 --> 00:45:41,930
Upwind.
Did a few sail changes.

723
00:45:41,968 --> 00:45:46,064
Now I'm ready to, uh, set a kite,
and take my shirt off, and go downwind.

724
00:45:53,680 --> 00:45:56,649
[Schubert] I had to start the race
down below. It was so light.

725
00:45:56,683 --> 00:45:59,618
I started thinking,
"I'm already missing the small things:

726
00:45:59,653 --> 00:46:01,780
Cheese pizza, HBO,

727
00:46:01,822 --> 00:46:04,086
that beautiful woman
from Gladstone's."

728
00:46:06,860 --> 00:46:09,886
[Kirby] The whole mindset
in offshore sailing

729
00:46:09,930 --> 00:46:12,899
is you start to find
what your limits are.

730
00:46:12,933 --> 00:46:14,457
How far can you push yourself,

731
00:46:14,501 --> 00:46:16,264
how many hours can you
work without rest,

732
00:46:16,303 --> 00:46:18,396
how long can you go without food?

733
00:46:18,438 --> 00:46:22,272
And mentally you have the ability
to set your mind on infinity.

734
00:46:22,309 --> 00:46:24,072
That's a winning combination.

735
00:46:38,792 --> 00:46:41,352
<i>[Fielding] No family and friends</i>
<i>from back home.</i>

736
00:46:41,395 --> 00:46:44,558
- <i>[Tulloch] No Starbucks.</i>
- <i>[Fielding] No music.</i>

737
00:46:44,598 --> 00:46:48,090
- <i>[Tulloch] No movies.</i>
- <i>[Fielding] No surfing.</i>

738
00:46:50,404 --> 00:46:52,634
<i>All that matters is</i>
<i>the Diamond Head buoy.</i>

739
00:47:02,149 --> 00:47:04,811
[Will] lt... It feels amazing
to be on this boat.

740
00:47:04,851 --> 00:47:09,652
Being on a crew with a bunch of young
kids is kinda the coolest thing,

741
00:47:09,689 --> 00:47:11,657
'cause you really build a team

742
00:47:11,691 --> 00:47:13,716
and not just sail with a bunch of guys

743
00:47:13,760 --> 00:47:16,058
who are telling you
what to do all the time,

744
00:47:16,096 --> 00:47:18,428
but you all kind of feel
like you're part of it

745
00:47:18,465 --> 00:47:21,764
and feel like we have a shot
at doing really well in this race.

746
00:47:34,080 --> 00:47:37,675
Piet and Jeremy and I, we're at a very
big decision-making point right now,

747
00:47:37,717 --> 00:47:40,151
we need to choose between
the northern and southern route.

748
00:47:40,187 --> 00:47:41,620
There's no middle-of-the-road route.

749
00:47:41,655 --> 00:47:43,885
'Cause we have a local
weak high-pressure

750
00:47:43,924 --> 00:47:48,088
that has been living in the middle of
the wing existing tracks for Transpac.

751
00:47:49,863 --> 00:47:52,559
The history of the race
has always been the team

752
00:47:52,599 --> 00:47:54,624
that makes that choice
at the right time,

753
00:47:54,668 --> 00:47:56,636
whether it's to go south, to go north.

754
00:47:56,670 --> 00:47:59,969
It's a defining moment, and it's
one of those moments you back up,

755
00:48:00,006 --> 00:48:01,997
and that's where
the race is won and lost.

756
00:48:02,042 --> 00:48:04,010
What I'm saying is,
you know, if we're...

757
00:48:04,044 --> 00:48:07,013
If we're gonna be in the synoptic,
we're on the southern route...

758
00:48:07,047 --> 00:48:11,074
[Sanderson] They really gotta make sure
that they stay in the pack,

759
00:48:11,117 --> 00:48:12,641
don't make some dumb mistake

760
00:48:12,686 --> 00:48:15,314
which suddenly drops them
a few miles behind,

761
00:48:15,355 --> 00:48:16,982
and then they're on the back foot.

762
00:48:17,023 --> 00:48:20,550
They don't need to be leading,
they just need to be in the hunt.

763
00:48:20,594 --> 00:48:25,190
Everything we've always learned and
talked about is not to get that close.

764
00:48:25,232 --> 00:48:27,666
Jeremy, what do you think?

765
00:48:27,701 --> 00:48:28,929
South.

766
00:48:28,969 --> 00:48:32,336
We just wanna stay away
from this, uh, high.

767
00:48:39,045 --> 00:48:41,411
[Van Os] Big fish last night
jumped out of the water,

768
00:48:41,448 --> 00:48:43,678
- hit the sail right there.
- [Tulloch] Hit the sail, I know.

769
00:48:43,717 --> 00:48:45,878
What about that whale?
That was a whale, wasn't it?

770
00:48:45,919 --> 00:48:46,943
[Van Os] I thought so.

771
00:48:46,987 --> 00:48:49,421
[Tulloch] Ten feet from our boat.
Trim on.

772
00:48:50,724 --> 00:48:54,592
Trim? Trim?

773
00:48:54,628 --> 00:48:55,652
Trim.

774
00:48:56,630 --> 00:48:58,222
[Van Os] You gotta use
your big girl voice.

775
00:48:58,265 --> 00:48:59,755
[Tulloch] Hold there.

776
00:49:02,135 --> 00:49:04,763
[Towill] It's the first morning,
the sun just came up.

777
00:49:04,804 --> 00:49:07,773
At sunset last night
we could see ten, 15 boats,

778
00:49:07,807 --> 00:49:09,968
and now we've got no one in sight.

779
00:49:10,010 --> 00:49:11,637
Position report comes out
in a little while,

780
00:49:11,678 --> 00:49:13,441
we'll see how we're doing
against our competitors.

781
00:49:14,881 --> 00:49:16,576
[Branning] <i>Alaska Eagle, Alaska Eagle,</i>

782
00:49:16,616 --> 00:49:20,609
this is <i>Morning Light</i> Whiskey Delta
Delta five one seven eight.

783
00:49:20,654 --> 00:49:24,090
<i>[man]</i> Morning Light, <i>have you loud</i>
<i>and clear. Welcome and good morning.</i>

784
00:49:24,124 --> 00:49:25,955
<i>Your position.</i>

785
00:49:25,992 --> 00:49:29,723
Thirty-two one-nine north.

786
00:49:29,763 --> 00:49:33,255
One-one-nine five-six west.

787
00:49:34,234 --> 00:49:36,259
<i>[man]</i> Morning Light,
<i>thank you very much.</i>

788
00:49:38,538 --> 00:49:39,630
[Wilmot] Where are they?

789
00:49:39,673 --> 00:49:41,766
[Branning] <i>Samba Pa Ti's</i>
range and bearing.

790
00:49:41,808 --> 00:49:44,777
Range: 20 miles.
Bearing: 223.

791
00:49:44,811 --> 00:49:46,278
[Wilmot] So they're going up.

792
00:49:46,313 --> 00:49:48,679
[Branning] Directly ahead of us,
20 miles. Yeah.

793
00:49:48,715 --> 00:49:51,548
- They're 19 miles ahead.
- Yeah.

794
00:49:51,585 --> 00:49:53,314
[Wilmot groans]

795
00:49:53,353 --> 00:49:56,618
[Branning] We need to know who's goin'
north and who's goin' south.

796
00:50:00,794 --> 00:50:02,557
You see what's for dinner?

797
00:50:06,466 --> 00:50:09,162
Eleven forty-one on Monday,

798
00:50:09,202 --> 00:50:11,432
and, uh, that means lunchtime.

799
00:50:11,471 --> 00:50:15,100
So, the first gourmet meal

800
00:50:15,141 --> 00:50:17,575
of this big event

801
00:50:17,611 --> 00:50:20,171
will be, uh,
beef stroganoff with noodles.

802
00:50:20,213 --> 00:50:22,306
My favorite.

803
00:50:22,349 --> 00:50:25,785
[Branning] This southerly route
doesn't look so good. It's nine knots.

804
00:50:29,155 --> 00:50:31,919
I wanna go fast.
That's 20 knots up there right now.

805
00:50:31,958 --> 00:50:35,655
- [Wilmot] What, going north?
- [Branning] Going more northerly, yeah.

806
00:50:35,695 --> 00:50:38,323
It's like taking
a right turn right now.

807
00:50:38,365 --> 00:50:40,390
It's all in or nothing, man.

808
00:50:40,433 --> 00:50:42,731
Figure I could just ask right now.

809
00:50:42,769 --> 00:50:45,067
I mean, it's been an hour
since we've been...

810
00:50:45,105 --> 00:50:47,938
Started this discussion,
you know.

811
00:50:47,974 --> 00:50:50,807
We haven't heard from them
what we should be doing.

812
00:50:50,844 --> 00:50:52,812
[indistinct]

813
00:50:52,846 --> 00:50:56,009
I think I should just start smashing
my foot on the deck.

814
00:50:56,049 --> 00:50:58,609
- That's not... Uh, yeah.
- No, they hate that.

815
00:50:58,652 --> 00:50:59,676
Yeah.

816
00:51:02,122 --> 00:51:04,613
- [Wilmot] What do you guys think?
- [Branning] If we do this,

817
00:51:04,658 --> 00:51:06,182
this is the whole race right here.

818
00:51:10,597 --> 00:51:13,361
[Kane] Here we go, guys.
Let's go!

819
00:51:13,400 --> 00:51:15,595
Are we basically deciding
to go north now, or...

820
00:51:15,635 --> 00:51:16,659
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

821
00:51:17,604 --> 00:51:19,231
What's the heading? 245?

822
00:51:19,272 --> 00:51:21,570
Hey, lads!
We're going north.

823
00:51:21,608 --> 00:51:23,200
- Ease the sheets!
- Full upwind.

824
00:51:23,243 --> 00:51:24,574
North. Full upwind.

825
00:51:33,553 --> 00:51:36,852
[Van Os] This is a slow way
to go across the Pacific, huh?

826
00:51:40,427 --> 00:51:42,657
[Kane] Are we going to Alaska?

827
00:51:45,932 --> 00:51:48,162
About 12 hours later,
the kids changed their mind

828
00:51:48,201 --> 00:51:49,498
and they headed north again.

829
00:51:50,537 --> 00:51:53,904
What it told me was that, you know,
there was somebody home on the boat.

830
00:51:53,940 --> 00:51:57,376
They were thinking, they were making
decisions, they were doing stuff.

831
00:51:57,410 --> 00:51:58,877
Then they headed north again.

832
00:52:04,050 --> 00:52:06,211
[Enright] You know what I just thought
of, but I don't know why?

833
00:52:06,252 --> 00:52:08,652
You know why the Chevy Nova
didn't work in Mexico?

834
00:52:08,688 --> 00:52:10,212
[Towill] Yeah. All right.

835
00:52:10,256 --> 00:52:13,555
[Enright] 'Cause <i>"no va"</i>
means, like, "no go."

836
00:52:13,593 --> 00:52:15,424
Why'd you buy a car
called the "no go"?

837
00:52:15,462 --> 00:52:16,486
[laughter]

838
00:52:23,803 --> 00:52:27,000
[Tulloch] Freakin' dying. Quickly.

839
00:52:27,040 --> 00:52:29,702
[music slowing down]

840
00:52:30,677 --> 00:52:33,510
[Schubert] No way.
This wind's just gonna die.

841
00:52:53,633 --> 00:52:55,726
[Enright] "Graham,
the race has been slow.

842
00:52:55,769 --> 00:52:58,033
I'm sure you're aware of this.

843
00:52:58,071 --> 00:53:01,268
The brain trust has just indicated
that the next 18 hours or so

844
00:53:01,307 --> 00:53:03,400
may dictate the entire
outcome of the race.

845
00:53:03,443 --> 00:53:06,640
I hope your fingers are crossed
and you're following along at home

846
00:53:06,679 --> 00:53:09,580
in Hawaii or wherever you are
at this present point in time.

847
00:53:09,616 --> 00:53:11,584
My feet are just starting to smell.

848
00:53:11,618 --> 00:53:14,587
I'm using precious off-watch time
to communicate with you.

849
00:53:14,621 --> 00:53:16,316
I guess that's all for now.

850
00:53:16,356 --> 00:53:18,722
Adios from the nerve center.
Talk to you later."

851
00:53:26,466 --> 00:53:29,492
[Kane] This is bad.
Real bad.

852
00:53:34,340 --> 00:53:38,106
[Wilmot] You think this is the first
time this has happened in the Transpac?

853
00:53:39,412 --> 00:53:41,846
It'll be one that
they're gonna remember,

854
00:53:41,881 --> 00:53:44,850
- and Stan's gonna harken back to.
- Yeah, this is crazy.

855
00:53:44,884 --> 00:53:47,853
Any way you approach this race,
you have to slice through that.

856
00:53:47,887 --> 00:53:49,650
[Van Os] That turn's gonna cost us.

857
00:53:51,024 --> 00:53:52,992
[Branning] No use talking about it now.

858
00:53:54,027 --> 00:53:56,689
<i>[#</i> Zero 7: <i>In The Waiting Line]</i>

859
00:54:12,912 --> 00:54:15,904
Oh, this is painful
circumstances right now.

860
00:54:15,949 --> 00:54:18,417
We've got our opponents
out to the south of us

861
00:54:18,451 --> 00:54:21,477
who are screaming along with a kite.

862
00:54:21,521 --> 00:54:24,354
Guys out to the north
of us are in more breeze.

863
00:54:34,801 --> 00:54:36,428
This is frustrating.

864
00:54:49,082 --> 00:54:50,572
We took a gamble.

865
00:54:52,018 --> 00:54:55,112
[groans] It was a big move at the time.

866
00:54:55,154 --> 00:54:57,952
Now we're fighting for the past two days
to get out of it.

867
00:54:59,192 --> 00:55:01,660
And we should've pretended
we were on train tracks

868
00:55:01,694 --> 00:55:04,185
and just trusted it.
Didn't look this light.

869
00:55:06,032 --> 00:55:09,798
But it is, and here we are.
Can't escape it now.

870
00:55:16,843 --> 00:55:20,244
- [Branning] We should've known better.
- Yeah.

871
00:55:20,280 --> 00:55:22,612
We can second-guess
ourselves all the way home.

872
00:55:24,117 --> 00:55:27,814
We'll be lucky to make it
to Hawaii in ten days, now.

873
00:55:34,594 --> 00:55:36,289
[Welch] I got a question for ya.

874
00:55:36,329 --> 00:55:37,694
- [Kane] Yeah?
- [Welch] Are we effed?

875
00:55:37,730 --> 00:55:39,493
- [Kane] Huh?
- [Welch] Are we effed?

876
00:55:39,532 --> 00:55:41,557
- [Kane] We don't think so. Yeah.
- [Welch] Really?

877
00:55:41,601 --> 00:55:44,331
You think... you think
that we can reel in <i>Samba?</i>

878
00:55:44,370 --> 00:55:46,031
[Kane] Uh, we'll see.

879
00:55:46,072 --> 00:55:48,302
[Welch] We're not, like,
out in the middle of nowhere?

880
00:55:48,341 --> 00:55:50,571
- [Kane] No, we're not.
- [Welch] You sure?

881
00:56:05,158 --> 00:56:06,921
[Wilmot] Big wind shift
here, guys.

882
00:56:06,960 --> 00:56:08,689
[Branning] Come on.
Let's do this.

883
00:56:08,728 --> 00:56:10,787
[Kane] OK, tacking the boat.

884
00:56:10,830 --> 00:56:12,320
Going to Hawaii.

885
00:56:13,633 --> 00:56:15,066
[Schubert] Finally!

886
00:56:17,036 --> 00:56:19,197
[Wilmot] We're almost
pointing at the mark.

887
00:56:23,376 --> 00:56:26,402
[Tulloch] Guys, when you have dinner,
clean your stuff, please.

888
00:56:26,446 --> 00:56:28,710
- Oh! Oh-ho!
- Whoo! [laughs]

889
00:56:37,023 --> 00:56:38,854
[Branning] It's Wednesday morning.

890
00:56:38,891 --> 00:56:41,917
Uh, just got done doin' the roll call.

891
00:56:41,961 --> 00:56:43,895
Not to be, like, uh, Debbie Downer,

892
00:56:43,930 --> 00:56:46,626
I thought we were gonna be smoked
after yesterday.

893
00:56:48,801 --> 00:56:51,702
[Welch] Did you hear from Branning,
the position report?

894
00:56:51,738 --> 00:56:53,831
- Brought some standings.
- Eh.

895
00:56:55,675 --> 00:56:59,111
We're first in division, 21 st in fleet.

896
00:57:00,480 --> 00:57:03,779
And <i>Samba's,</i> uh, second in division,
22nd in fleet.

897
00:57:03,816 --> 00:57:07,047
We have 1,742 miles to go,

898
00:57:07,086 --> 00:57:09,850
and they got 1,742 miles to go.

899
00:57:12,759 --> 00:57:14,693
[Schubert] Did anybody see that comin'?

900
00:57:14,727 --> 00:57:16,194
[Kane] Branning, you the man.

901
00:57:16,229 --> 00:57:17,753
Hi.

902
00:57:19,999 --> 00:57:21,466
Hi.

903
00:57:21,501 --> 00:57:23,799
Twelve hours ago we were all wrecked.

904
00:57:23,836 --> 00:57:26,737
Branning was ready to quit
sailing altogether.

905
00:57:26,773 --> 00:57:30,607
Very stressful.
Think I lost some hair.

906
00:57:31,511 --> 00:57:33,536
It was pretty miserable.

907
00:57:33,579 --> 00:57:36,707
We were over on port deck
going very slow.

908
00:57:36,749 --> 00:57:39,741
Now we've, uh, tacked over
onto starboard,

909
00:57:39,786 --> 00:57:42,220
and blue sky, it's beautiful. [laughs]

910
00:57:42,255 --> 00:57:46,055
Bit of a difference.
Sailing pretty good today.

911
00:57:46,092 --> 00:57:49,289
Emotional roller coaster through
and through, this bloody race.

912
00:57:51,497 --> 00:57:54,898
[upbeat music playing]

913
00:58:08,881 --> 00:58:10,849
Hey, Towiller.
We need you on deck, mate.

914
00:58:10,883 --> 00:58:13,249
- Coming.
- And you, too, Branning.

915
00:58:24,230 --> 00:58:27,427
- OK, you guys ready?
- Yeah. Ready in the pit.

916
00:58:27,467 --> 00:58:29,935
Hoist when ready, guys.

917
00:58:29,969 --> 00:58:33,769
- Bring it over.
- Go for it, go, go, go!

918
00:58:41,380 --> 00:58:42,938
Hold there, Towiller.

919
00:58:42,982 --> 00:58:45,143
Ease. Ease, Towill.

920
00:58:48,721 --> 00:58:52,555
[Welch] It's startin' to feel more
what I pictured Transpac to be like.

921
00:58:52,592 --> 00:58:56,551
We're going to, going to Hawaii,
and we're back in the game.

922
00:58:59,599 --> 00:59:01,726
We're gonna need
another human up here.

923
00:59:01,767 --> 00:59:05,168
- [indistinct]... more brace?
- More brace.

924
00:59:07,039 --> 00:59:10,475
[Wilmot] Piet, where's our <i>Morning Light</i>
logo on this kite?

925
00:59:10,510 --> 00:59:13,274
Get Charlie up.
Isn't he in charge of sails?

926
00:59:14,480 --> 00:59:17,711
The first kite we hoist in the Transpac
doesn't even have one.

927
00:59:30,029 --> 00:59:32,657
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] "Charles.</i>
<i>Thanks for the contact.</i>

928
00:59:32,698 --> 00:59:35,326
<i>Hawaii is fun.</i>

929
00:59:36,602 --> 00:59:38,467
<i>The Red Sox just won the World Series.</i>

930
00:59:38,504 --> 00:59:40,734
<i>And tell Welchy</i>
<i>the stock market burned down.</i>

931
00:59:40,773 --> 00:59:43,674
<i>I'm sorry, but there are</i>
<i>no more stocks. Period.</i>

932
00:59:44,844 --> 00:59:47,540
<i>Looks like you guys are going balls-out</i>
<i>on your route so far.</i>

933
00:59:47,580 --> 00:59:49,207
<i>Hope you're rationing.</i>

934
00:59:49,248 --> 00:59:52,149
<i>Everyone's either gonna say you're</i>
<i>brilliant or redheaded.</i>

935
00:59:52,185 --> 00:59:53,777
<i>But tell Fancypants not to worry.</i>

936
00:59:53,819 --> 00:59:56,219
<i>Statistics show that</i>
<i>30 percent of redheads..."</i>

937
00:59:58,925 --> 01:00:01,086
[Towill]
We had a beautiful sunset tonight.

938
01:00:01,127 --> 01:00:04,688
If you look over here,
you can see the-the moon, um,

939
01:00:04,730 --> 01:00:07,494
just glistening at the top of the...

940
01:00:07,533 --> 01:00:09,558
Top of the clouds as it's setting,

941
01:00:09,602 --> 01:00:13,561
and we've just got the slightest
little crescent new moon

942
01:00:13,606 --> 01:00:15,233
and it's absolutely beautiful.

943
01:00:15,274 --> 01:00:19,108
It's making a little spotlight
down on the water and...

944
01:00:19,145 --> 01:00:21,170
Beautiful stuff out here, man.

945
01:00:30,990 --> 01:00:33,788
[Enright] I just got an e-mail
from Graham. He wrote back.

946
01:00:33,826 --> 01:00:35,953
Our race so far,
he wishes he was with us.

947
01:00:35,995 --> 01:00:39,522
Clearly he's checking the grids, not
that he knows exactly what they mean.

948
01:00:39,565 --> 01:00:41,965
He's into it and,
based on our track,

949
01:00:42,001 --> 01:00:45,368
people are gonna either think we're
brilliant or a bunch of redheads.

950
01:00:45,404 --> 01:00:47,599
- But, redheads tend to...
- [laughter]

951
01:00:47,640 --> 01:00:50,108
Thirty percent of all redheads
turn out to live...

952
01:00:50,142 --> 01:00:51,905
...healthy, productive lives
or something.

953
01:00:51,944 --> 01:00:54,469
- Yes.
- But, yeah, he seems in good spirits.

954
01:00:54,513 --> 01:00:55,878
- [Kane] Trim up.
- [Welch] Good.

955
01:00:55,915 --> 01:00:57,678
[Towill] That's good.
That's really good.

956
01:00:59,719 --> 01:01:02,415
Whoo! It's a scorcher!

957
01:01:02,455 --> 01:01:05,686
[Kane] It's gonna be a "Triple-H" day:
hazy, hot, and humid.

958
01:01:05,725 --> 01:01:09,183
[Branning] I gotta take a shower...
I gotta do some sort of bathing today.

959
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:15,627
[Van Os] Today was the first day
where it's really hot.

960
01:01:15,668 --> 01:01:19,900
Woke up and it was sweaty and nasty
down below, which is not very fun.

961
01:01:19,939 --> 01:01:21,736
[Wilmot] We share bunks downstairs,

962
01:01:21,774 --> 01:01:24,709
so your person opposite you
gets a little too smelly,

963
01:01:24,744 --> 01:01:26,803
then, you know, it's miserable.

964
01:01:26,846 --> 01:01:32,307
<i>[#</i> Buzzcocks:
<i>Everybody's Happy Nowadays]</i>

965
01:01:32,351 --> 01:01:35,548
<i>Big Michiganders Gone Wild.</i> [laughs]

966
01:01:39,992 --> 01:01:43,052
[Welch] I think a little shower,
brushing your teeth,

967
01:01:43,095 --> 01:01:45,928
besides the health part of it,
just kinda keeps you going.

968
01:01:45,965 --> 01:01:48,490
I mean, it's a... freshens you up.

969
01:01:57,176 --> 01:02:00,805
Today was awesome. I got a shower,
I got to shave...

970
01:02:00,846 --> 01:02:02,746
[Kane] Got a hot date tonight, Genny?

971
01:02:02,782 --> 01:02:06,149
[laughs] I groomed myself
while all the boys watched.

972
01:02:06,185 --> 01:02:10,747
No, I'm just kidding. Um, but it was
sweet to finally get a shower today.

973
01:02:10,790 --> 01:02:13,816
And then, obviously, all the...
all the... Trim.

974
01:02:13,859 --> 01:02:17,090
Um, I feel like

975
01:02:17,129 --> 01:02:20,496
we're all in a pretty good mood
and we're all clean and happy.

976
01:02:26,939 --> 01:02:31,103
[Kane] Our competition, <i>Samba,</i>
is, uh, right above us,

977
01:02:31,143 --> 01:02:34,909
so there's a lot of pressure
on the bow team at nighttime.

978
01:02:34,947 --> 01:02:39,111
Tonight's gonna be a big opportunity
for either one of us to push away.

979
01:02:39,151 --> 01:02:44,589
Nighttime racing is, uh,
where you can really make huge gains.

980
01:02:44,623 --> 01:02:46,454
And it's hard to see your competitors.

981
01:02:46,492 --> 01:02:50,053
They can, uh, pull a maneuver
without you seeing.

982
01:02:51,997 --> 01:02:55,194
[Kane] Last night was our first night
with the spinnaker, and it feels off.

983
01:02:55,234 --> 01:02:58,203
We just need to kinda get with it.
Everyone was running around

984
01:02:58,237 --> 01:03:01,468
like chickens with their heads
cut off, including myself.

985
01:03:01,507 --> 01:03:06,604
[Wilmot] If we go to sleep for two hours
we could lose seven miles like that.

986
01:03:06,645 --> 01:03:09,671
[Welch] These guys on <i>Samba,</i>
they're all fantastic sailors.

987
01:03:09,715 --> 01:03:12,275
And, you know, we're all
really new to it, I guess.

988
01:03:12,318 --> 01:03:16,152
And we've gotta really make sure that
we, you know, try and keep our edge.

989
01:03:16,188 --> 01:03:17,883
Who knows?
You might see us tonight

990
01:03:17,923 --> 01:03:20,323
jibing a couple of times
on random shifts,

991
01:03:20,359 --> 01:03:22,623
just to get away
from these guys to windward

992
01:03:22,661 --> 01:03:24,424
and catch 'em
with their pants down.

993
01:03:24,463 --> 01:03:26,556
[Welch] I like where your head's at.

994
01:03:26,599 --> 01:03:27,623
[Kane] Yeah.

995
01:03:30,903 --> 01:03:32,837
[Branning] This is pretty much, I guess,

996
01:03:32,872 --> 01:03:36,069
as about as far away from land
as you can get anywhere on the planet,

997
01:03:36,108 --> 01:03:38,906
- where we are right now.
- [Wilmot] Yeah. Halfway point.

998
01:03:39,879 --> 01:03:41,574
Pretty amazing, isn't it?

999
01:04:03,369 --> 01:04:06,930
<i>Samba Pa Ti,</i> we just saw. We can see
their running lights right over there.

1000
01:04:06,972 --> 01:04:09,065
They're behind us and going south.

1001
01:04:12,511 --> 01:04:15,674
[Tulloch] So it's Day Six,
we just saw <i>Samba,</i>

1002
01:04:15,714 --> 01:04:17,841
and we're less than
a mile away from them.

1003
01:04:23,055 --> 01:04:27,389
<i>Samba's</i> come astern of us
and jibed right on our line.

1004
01:04:30,463 --> 01:04:31,828
Trim up.

1005
01:04:35,835 --> 01:04:37,496
[Tulloch] The pressure's really been up.

1006
01:04:37,536 --> 01:04:39,970
The... the intensity
on the boat is super high.

1007
01:04:40,005 --> 01:04:41,996
We're just pushing, pushing,
pushing all the time.

1008
01:04:42,041 --> 01:04:43,065
Hold.

1009
01:05:10,236 --> 01:05:12,864
Trim up.
Big trim, big trim.

1010
01:05:12,905 --> 01:05:15,533
<i>[#</i> Massive Attack: <i>Angel]</i>

1011
01:05:23,048 --> 01:05:24,413
[Van Os] Nice.

1012
01:05:51,710 --> 01:05:54,440
[Van Os laughs] I can't believe
that boat's right there.

1013
01:05:55,481 --> 01:05:57,449
How close do you think they are?

1014
01:05:57,483 --> 01:06:00,281
Quarter of a mile?
Not even 200 yards?

1015
01:06:00,319 --> 01:06:02,879
[Van Os] Nice to have someone
right there to push you.

1016
01:06:06,592 --> 01:06:08,787
Just think, we're making 'em
work for their money today.

1017
01:06:08,827 --> 01:06:09,851
- Yup.
- Yeah.

1018
01:06:09,895 --> 01:06:11,328
- Don't stop.
- [laughs]

1019
01:06:11,363 --> 01:06:12,853
Ooh. Bolt.

1020
01:06:14,266 --> 01:06:16,962
[Towill] It's a thousand miles
into the race.

1021
01:06:17,002 --> 01:06:19,903
<i>Samba's</i> closer to us now
than they were at the starting line.

1022
01:06:19,939 --> 01:06:23,670
Trim up. Pull back.

1023
01:06:23,709 --> 01:06:26,735
[Van Os] Wow. Doing 13 knots.
The whole Pacific.

1024
01:06:26,779 --> 01:06:28,838
The boat, two boat lengths from you.

1025
01:06:30,983 --> 01:06:32,746
[Kane] I'm gonna be a pro sailor.

1026
01:06:32,785 --> 01:06:35,845
Forget landscape design,
I'm doing this for the rest of my life.

1027
01:07:04,750 --> 01:07:07,116
[Wilmot] I think the owner's
on the wheel.

1028
01:07:09,688 --> 01:07:11,918
Lock it. Big trim, big trim,
big trim, big trim.

1029
01:07:11,957 --> 01:07:13,720
[Van Os] No, no, no, not now, not now.

1030
01:07:13,759 --> 01:07:16,387
- Got it. Hold.
- Just keep your cool, Piet.

1031
01:07:19,999 --> 01:07:22,194
[Van Os] We just got rolled,
unfortunately.

1032
01:07:22,234 --> 01:07:24,259
[Wilmot] Pretty bloody close.

1033
01:07:25,904 --> 01:07:28,134
I can see the smiles
on their faces.

1034
01:07:30,442 --> 01:07:32,740
[Fielding] That one guy
gave us the thumbs up.

1035
01:07:32,778 --> 01:07:34,143
[Kane] That's pretty cool.

1036
01:07:35,280 --> 01:07:37,145
What are they doing here?

1037
01:07:40,452 --> 01:07:43,888
- And not that right now.
- Nah, they're filling the space left.

1038
01:07:43,922 --> 01:07:46,857
- They only have one sheet on.
- Yeah, that would verify it.

1039
01:07:46,892 --> 01:07:48,416
- [Will] Trim.
- [Towill] Yeah.

1040
01:07:48,460 --> 01:07:50,155
We'll take a fast-way line to Hawaii.

1041
01:07:50,195 --> 01:07:51,958
[Kane] Bold. What's going on?

1042
01:07:53,599 --> 01:07:55,931
- [Van Os] Wow, look at that.
- What are they doing?

1043
01:07:55,968 --> 01:07:58,402
[Welch] They're animals,
and they even got Kilroy out.

1044
01:07:58,437 --> 01:08:00,029
[Towill] I think they lost a halyard.

1045
01:08:00,072 --> 01:08:01,835
[Wilmot] They lost their kite.

1046
01:08:01,874 --> 01:08:04,502
[Kane] They got something
on the rudder, I don't know.

1047
01:08:20,759 --> 01:08:24,195
[Kilroy] We had a sea serpent.
And it was wrapped around our rudder.

1048
01:08:24,229 --> 01:08:26,094
And they looked at us like we were nuts.

1049
01:08:26,131 --> 01:08:27,655
We went a little bit to leeward.

1050
01:08:27,700 --> 01:08:29,725
I haven't had that kind of experience

1051
01:08:29,768 --> 01:08:32,259
with another boat
in the middle of the ocean before.

1052
01:08:34,039 --> 01:08:36,234
[Enright] That was a super
professional move.

1053
01:08:36,275 --> 01:08:37,435
[Tulloch] What happened?

1054
01:08:37,476 --> 01:08:39,205
[Enright] They thought they
had something on their rudder,

1055
01:08:39,244 --> 01:08:41,337
so they went kite down
on deck, staysail in.

1056
01:08:41,380 --> 01:08:44,440
Back down, staysail out.
Bow down, kite up. See ya.

1057
01:08:49,054 --> 01:08:51,887
- [Van Os] God.
- [Branning] They're kinda truckin'.

1058
01:08:51,924 --> 01:08:54,757
It's like they can't sail at night,
but then the day comes

1059
01:08:54,793 --> 01:08:57,626
and they're like, "OK,
I guess we'll start sailing again."

1060
01:08:57,663 --> 01:08:58,994
Then they sail pretty well.

1061
01:08:59,031 --> 01:09:01,363
[Towill] I feel like
they gain at night.

1062
01:09:04,737 --> 01:09:06,967
<i>[Tulloch] It's been</i>
<i>a really intense 24 hours.</i>

1063
01:09:07,005 --> 01:09:09,496
<i>We've got these pro sailors,</i>
<i>this super-fast boat.</i>

1064
01:09:09,541 --> 01:09:12,237
<i>And actually have crossed paths</i>
<i>with them this morning</i>

1065
01:09:12,277 --> 01:09:14,541
<i>and then fallen behind them</i>
<i>in two big maneuvers,</i>

1066
01:09:14,580 --> 01:09:17,447
<i>and then now to be beating them</i>
<i>again after the last 12 hours.</i>

1067
01:09:17,483 --> 01:09:20,577
<i>It's really keeping us motivated</i>
<i>and keeping us going.</i>

1068
01:09:24,156 --> 01:09:27,023
[Branning] To give you an example
of what we're up against,

1069
01:09:27,059 --> 01:09:29,323
- the navigator for <i>Samba...</i>
- [chuckles]

1070
01:09:29,361 --> 01:09:32,455
...wrote the program
that we use to navigate,

1071
01:09:32,498 --> 01:09:34,989
that all the boats use
to navigate in the Volvo,

1072
01:09:35,033 --> 01:09:38,196
the around-the-world races,
in the America's Cup, stuff like that.

1073
01:09:38,237 --> 01:09:40,671
- So...
- It's cool to be racing against him,

1074
01:09:40,706 --> 01:09:42,833
have him right there.
Thinking with him.

1075
01:09:42,875 --> 01:09:44,638
[Branning] That was a cool feeling.

1076
01:09:44,676 --> 01:09:46,906
[Towill] What is <i>Samba Pa Ti?</i>
Is it a song or something?

1077
01:09:46,945 --> 01:09:49,607
[Schubert] <i>Samba Pa Ti</i> is a great song
by Carlos Santana.

1078
01:09:49,648 --> 01:09:51,206
[Tulloch] Trim.

1079
01:09:51,250 --> 01:09:52,740
Hold that.

1080
01:09:54,186 --> 01:09:55,414
Trim, Bear, trim.

1081
01:09:57,055 --> 01:09:58,317
Pull.

1082
01:09:58,357 --> 01:10:01,918
[exhales] I can't keep
trimming it like this.

1083
01:10:01,960 --> 01:10:04,861
It's... you're... You require a lot more
trim than most people,

1084
01:10:04,897 --> 01:10:08,162
and it's exhausting.
I know you're trying to do the fastest,

1085
01:10:08,200 --> 01:10:11,226
but... we're just going to
have to rotate more or something.

1086
01:10:12,604 --> 01:10:13,866
[Tulloch] Trim.

1087
01:10:15,808 --> 01:10:17,173
- Pull.
- [Kane] Damn.

1088
01:10:18,844 --> 01:10:21,472
[Towill] She's drunk on estrogen.

1089
01:10:21,513 --> 01:10:23,242
- [laughs]
- Put her down.

1090
01:10:24,750 --> 01:10:27,810
How would you feel if you were
the only guy on an all-girl boat?

1091
01:10:27,853 --> 01:10:30,481
[Branning] I'll take miserable
for 100, Alex.

1092
01:10:30,522 --> 01:10:32,080
[laughter]

1093
01:10:32,124 --> 01:10:36,754
We think Genny's had the better deal
than we would on the other end.

1094
01:10:36,795 --> 01:10:39,229
[Van Os] Who wants to
with his hands crossed?

1095
01:10:39,264 --> 01:10:43,030
[laughs] This is like a fireside
session here, a fireside chat.

1096
01:10:43,068 --> 01:10:45,366
Well, really, hmm, uh...

1097
01:10:45,404 --> 01:10:48,498
You know, obviously none of us
know exactly how it is to be Genny,

1098
01:10:48,540 --> 01:10:50,735
but it's got to be
a little more difficult...

1099
01:10:50,776 --> 01:10:53,142
Genny takes it pretty well
for being the only girl.

1100
01:10:53,178 --> 01:10:55,237
Spectacular. She's a trouper.

1101
01:10:55,280 --> 01:10:57,612
Not meaning to be mean,
but we give her a lot of...

1102
01:10:57,649 --> 01:11:00,948
...just, you know, out of,
being, you know, teammates.

1103
01:11:00,986 --> 01:11:04,012
It would be very interesting to see,
you know...

1104
01:11:04,056 --> 01:11:05,921
To be on the opposite
side of... of...

1105
01:11:05,958 --> 01:11:07,823
[Towill] I wouldn't
want to do it at all.

1106
01:11:07,860 --> 01:11:10,590
Dude, if I could do this again
with 15 girls, I'd do it.

1107
01:11:12,097 --> 01:11:14,429
- It wouldn't be the same.
- It wouldn't be.

1108
01:11:14,466 --> 01:11:16,229
[Welch] Little does
<i>Samba</i> know what

1109
01:11:16,268 --> 01:11:17,895
we're talking about
while we were drag racing.

1110
01:11:25,277 --> 01:11:27,905
[Wilmot] Y'all have seen
the standings this morning.

1111
01:11:27,946 --> 01:11:29,379
We're still in good shape.

1112
01:11:29,414 --> 01:11:32,178
Believe it or not, even with <i>Samba's</i>
advantage right now

1113
01:11:32,217 --> 01:11:33,980
we still have them uncorrected.

1114
01:11:34,019 --> 01:11:36,954
But they are making a charge for it,
and we have to, too.

1115
01:11:36,989 --> 01:11:40,390
Let's not give in.
We're in second place.

1116
01:11:40,425 --> 01:11:42,825
<i>Samba</i> is just there, the big trophy.

1117
01:11:42,861 --> 01:11:45,625
So, let's just get our heads high,

1118
01:11:45,664 --> 01:11:48,690
and let's just push into this. OK, guys?

1119
01:11:55,641 --> 01:11:58,804
- Shoops, did they just jibe?
- [Schubert] Yes.

1120
01:11:58,844 --> 01:12:01,210
- [Wilmot] They did?
- [Schubert] Yes.

1121
01:12:02,447 --> 01:12:04,608
Gutsiest move I ever saw.

1122
01:12:08,687 --> 01:12:10,314
Shoops, take the wheel, mate.

1123
01:12:10,355 --> 01:12:13,586
B-Man. Jess. You're not
rolling that, are you?

1124
01:12:13,625 --> 01:12:14,649
No. No.

1125
01:12:14,693 --> 01:12:16,854
[Wilmot] Chuck it in the bag.
B-Man, I need you up here.

1126
01:12:18,897 --> 01:12:20,558
B-man, I said I needed you, mate.

1127
01:12:20,599 --> 01:12:21,759
That's not what I heard.

1128
01:12:21,800 --> 01:12:24,166
- [Wilmot] Yes, it is.
- [Branning] I can't hear ya.

1129
01:12:24,202 --> 01:12:25,430
[Wilmot] Come here.

1130
01:12:28,674 --> 01:12:31,234
Why have they jibed already?

1131
01:12:31,276 --> 01:12:32,903
What are you not telling me?

1132
01:12:35,213 --> 01:12:38,979
- His tack's at 290.
- The pressure's over there.

1133
01:12:39,017 --> 01:12:40,985
Is it worth taking it to get there?

1134
01:12:42,020 --> 01:12:44,181
[Branning] The Troll Nazi's back.

1135
01:12:44,222 --> 01:12:46,850
[Schubert] The thing is,
you can't get pissed though.

1136
01:12:46,892 --> 01:12:48,826
- [Towill] He, uh...
- [Schubert] It's always a good point.

1137
01:12:48,860 --> 01:12:51,090
It's always in the interest of speed.

1138
01:12:55,434 --> 01:12:58,835
[Wilmot] OK, guys.
We cleared for a jibe? Let's do it.

1139
01:12:58,870 --> 01:13:00,565
Let it go. Let it pass.

1140
01:13:02,674 --> 01:13:06,405
Smoothly, guys.
Make every movement smooth. OK?

1141
01:13:06,445 --> 01:13:08,743
I say it so many times.

1142
01:13:16,855 --> 01:13:19,085
[Schubert] <i>Samba</i> looked pretty far away.

1143
01:13:19,124 --> 01:13:21,820
[Kane] I just want them to go away.

1144
01:13:21,860 --> 01:13:24,226
So we can go back to sailing again.

1145
01:13:31,269 --> 01:13:32,634
Day nine.

1146
01:13:33,472 --> 01:13:35,702
Eleven... twent... Elev...

1147
01:13:35,741 --> 01:13:37,572
I got 11:30.

1148
01:13:37,609 --> 01:13:40,772
And this race is taking way too long.

1149
01:13:43,281 --> 01:13:46,375
I'll talk about food, how about I talk
about that? All right.

1150
01:13:47,219 --> 01:13:49,585
Well, today's the last day
of full meals.

1151
01:13:49,621 --> 01:13:51,714
So tomorrow
we're starting the rations.

1152
01:13:51,757 --> 01:13:54,920
So we've got... five meals.

1153
01:13:54,960 --> 01:14:00,455
And if that's three days,
then it's two meals a day.

1154
01:14:00,499 --> 01:14:04,629
So if we're doing two meals a day,
we should do it like 6am and 6pm.

1155
01:14:04,669 --> 01:14:06,227
- Yeah.
- Is that cool?

1156
01:14:06,271 --> 01:14:07,738
- Yeah.
- All right.

1157
01:14:15,981 --> 01:14:17,949
[Welch] Captain,
you ready for it now?

1158
01:14:17,983 --> 01:14:21,817
- Uh-uh. I'm eating dirt.
- [Schubert] It's really bad.

1159
01:14:28,527 --> 01:14:32,224
- Ah, that's not doing it.
- [Schubert] There's nothing else.

1160
01:14:32,264 --> 01:14:34,824
Do it with five of these in your mouth.

1161
01:14:39,805 --> 01:14:43,332
Yeah, there ya go.
Get rid of the aftertaste.

1162
01:14:43,375 --> 01:14:46,105
Uh, one of our little hobbies
that we've kinda picked up

1163
01:14:46,144 --> 01:14:49,011
is talking about the instantaneous
cravings that we have.

1164
01:14:49,047 --> 01:14:51,675
[Towill] Tuna salad sandwich.

1165
01:14:51,716 --> 01:14:53,741
Chocolate chip cookies
dipped in milk.

1166
01:14:53,785 --> 01:14:58,119
Dirt, tofu and... Uh.

1167
01:14:58,156 --> 01:15:01,319
- Jars of peanut butter.
- [Van Os] Peanut butter?

1168
01:15:01,359 --> 01:15:03,350
They just... [makes smash sound]
...protein.

1169
01:15:03,395 --> 01:15:06,694
Leave it out in the sun.
You get a peanut butter milkshake.

1170
01:15:06,731 --> 01:15:07,755
Look at the camera.

1171
01:15:07,799 --> 01:15:09,630
[Schubert] Hadn't eaten since
yesterday at 6:30.

1172
01:15:09,668 --> 01:15:12,159
It was awesome.
I didn't even chew.

1173
01:15:12,204 --> 01:15:16,573
I felt like my dog, Jake. When he eats,
he doesn't breathe, he just chews.

1174
01:15:16,608 --> 01:15:19,873
Eh, about half of it's chewed...
like, he chews about half.

1175
01:15:19,911 --> 01:15:23,711
Swallows the other half. No breathing
through the entire process.

1176
01:15:23,748 --> 01:15:26,080
Am I getting my point across?

1177
01:15:26,118 --> 01:15:28,746
This is how desperate we are for food.

1178
01:15:28,787 --> 01:15:32,723
We will eat the worst meal we've ever
had just because we're hungry,

1179
01:15:32,757 --> 01:15:35,021
and we won't have another meal
for eight hours.

1180
01:15:35,060 --> 01:15:37,324
Forcing it down your throat,
and at the end of it,

1181
01:15:37,362 --> 01:15:39,023
you feel like you're gonna throw up.

1182
01:15:39,064 --> 01:15:40,725
[Schubert] Bunch of us
are craving Reese's

1183
01:15:40,765 --> 01:15:45,065
and different types of pizza,
and Chinese food so.

1184
01:15:45,103 --> 01:15:48,231
[Branning] Chicken teriyaki
makes me want to vomit now.

1185
01:16:13,231 --> 01:16:14,459
<i>[Brant-Zawadzki] Hey, guys.</i>

1186
01:16:14,499 --> 01:16:17,332
<i>Steve-O wants to know</i>
<i>what's taking so long.</i>

1187
01:16:17,369 --> 01:16:20,861
<i>Oh, and ask Turtle if he'd rather have</i>
<i>a nice tall glass of Baileys</i>

1188
01:16:20,906 --> 01:16:23,534
<i>at the dock instead of a mai tai.</i>

1189
01:16:23,575 --> 01:16:27,067
<i>Don't worry about</i> Samba, <i>you guys can</i>
<i>lose them in those shoals up ahead.</i>

1190
01:16:27,112 --> 01:16:30,343
<i>If you don't know what that's from,</i>
<i>we're not friends anymore.</i>

1191
01:16:30,382 --> 01:16:34,819
<i>Godspeed</i> M.L., <i>stay fast</i>
<i>and don't eat each other.</i>

1192
01:16:34,853 --> 01:16:36,878
Signed, Pirate.

1193
01:16:53,872 --> 01:16:56,705
I'm a lucky bastard.
I'm lucky.

1194
01:17:05,817 --> 01:17:09,253
- Are you sure we're headed west?
- [laughs]

1195
01:17:09,287 --> 01:17:12,450
[Wilmot] Hawaii can't possibly
be this far away. Come on.

1196
01:17:12,490 --> 01:17:14,458
[Kane] Nothing's this far from land.

1197
01:17:14,492 --> 01:17:17,222
This is just stupid.
This is bad placement.

1198
01:17:17,262 --> 01:17:19,526
Why would you put islands
this far away from?

1199
01:17:19,564 --> 01:17:22,192
[Wilmot] Get Towiller up here.
Tell him to find Hawaii.

1200
01:17:22,234 --> 01:17:24,998
[Kane] Towiller, we need to pull
your house out the water.

1201
01:17:25,036 --> 01:17:27,470
Hello there!

1202
01:17:33,578 --> 01:17:36,706
[Branning] We sail, like, it's
a considerable part of the race

1203
01:17:36,748 --> 01:17:40,411
with <i>Samba</i> within ten miles
the whole time.

1204
01:17:40,452 --> 01:17:45,253
Last night they split
and went 120 miles to the south of us.

1205
01:17:45,290 --> 01:17:48,748
I mean, we're really far away
and they're all by themselves.

1206
01:17:49,961 --> 01:17:53,362
[Kilroy] We just felt that if we could
get south, we'd get better breeze.

1207
01:17:53,398 --> 01:17:56,799
Based upon the numbers, it wasn't
one of these, you know, roll the dice.

1208
01:17:56,835 --> 01:17:59,770
Yeah, like when you look
at these guys down here, <i>Samba Pa Ti,</i>

1209
01:17:59,804 --> 01:18:02,170
it looks like we've been given
a lottery ticket.

1210
01:18:02,207 --> 01:18:05,040
So I'm not, um, opposed
to just taking this down

1211
01:18:05,076 --> 01:18:06,907
and getting just in front of their nose.

1212
01:18:06,945 --> 01:18:10,381
And if it lifts... we're clean.
They're behind us.

1213
01:18:10,415 --> 01:18:14,044
If it knocks, we're on the mark.
In the bank.

1214
01:18:14,085 --> 01:18:16,178
- [Van Os] Yeah. [laughs]
- In the bank.

1215
01:18:16,221 --> 01:18:19,657
- Hang on to your butts.
- Oh.

1216
01:18:19,691 --> 01:18:21,124
Let's get these guys.

1217
01:18:25,630 --> 01:18:28,292
- [Schubert] Roll call is a dogfight.
- [Tulloch] Is it?

1218
01:18:28,333 --> 01:18:30,528
It's a friggin' dogfight.

1219
01:18:37,175 --> 01:18:41,805
[Wilmot] I'm gonna catch this boat up
in front of us, like it was my business.

1220
01:18:41,846 --> 01:18:45,873
We want both trophies. We want
to be the first TP52, and we want to...

1221
01:18:45,917 --> 01:18:50,183
Trim! ...win our... win our division
as well. That would be sweet.

1222
01:19:09,074 --> 01:19:11,542
[Kane] Have you seen
the squall over here?

1223
01:19:11,576 --> 01:19:13,908
[Kirby] Tropical squalls
can be critical.

1224
01:19:13,945 --> 01:19:17,745
You can gain dramatically
on competitors by playing the squalls.

1225
01:19:17,782 --> 01:19:19,181
[Fielding] There we go.

1226
01:19:19,217 --> 01:19:21,651
[Branning] Twenty knots.
That's directed to the reef.

1227
01:19:23,088 --> 01:19:25,249
[Wilmot] The sky's about to go boom.

1228
01:19:25,290 --> 01:19:30,250
- [Fielding] Who's the boom king?
- I'm the boom king!

1229
01:19:30,295 --> 01:19:31,922
Oh, baby!

1230
01:19:33,031 --> 01:19:36,194
- Hey, mister!
- Twenty-four knots.

1231
01:19:36,234 --> 01:19:38,668
[Towill] Hey, well,
why don't you just race, guy?

1232
01:19:38,703 --> 01:19:42,195
- [Wilmot] We're like modern pirates.
- [Towill] Pirates, man.

1233
01:19:42,240 --> 01:19:44,936
[Wilmot] We don't even own this boat.

1234
01:19:44,976 --> 01:19:48,969
[Kane] Breaking up
like an '80s band, baby.

1235
01:19:49,013 --> 01:19:51,140
[Schubert]
They'll have a comeback tour.

1236
01:19:51,182 --> 01:19:52,206
[Kane] Of course.

1237
01:19:52,250 --> 01:19:54,946
[Schubert] That's how
<i>Behind the Music</i> always ends.

1238
01:19:54,986 --> 01:19:57,216
[Branning] Yep, it was fun
while it lasted.

1239
01:19:59,124 --> 01:20:02,025
[Kane] Rainbow, baby.
It's getting close.

1240
01:20:02,060 --> 01:20:04,756
[Wilmot] Let's keep it
going fast. All day.

1241
01:20:12,670 --> 01:20:16,003
- I think I see land.
- Yeah.

1242
01:20:16,040 --> 01:20:18,440
- Whoo.
- I think I see a volcano.

1243
01:20:18,476 --> 01:20:21,309
- [Enright] Yeah.
- [Kane] Yeah!

1244
01:20:21,346 --> 01:20:24,645
Yeah, you can just see the edge of Maui
right on the bow right now.

1245
01:20:27,152 --> 01:20:28,915
[Schubert] That's Maui.

1246
01:20:28,953 --> 01:20:31,319
[Tulloch] Are we less than 12 hours?

1247
01:20:31,356 --> 01:20:34,519
[Kane] I'm going to the top of the rig
one last time.

1248
01:20:34,559 --> 01:20:37,187
One last time, forever.

1249
01:20:37,228 --> 01:20:39,788
[Welch] Turtle, let's take you
to the paradise city.

1250
01:20:44,035 --> 01:20:46,799
[Kane] Oh, my God.
It feels so good.

1251
01:20:46,838 --> 01:20:49,534
Gotta love it. Whoo!

1252
01:20:52,510 --> 01:20:54,341
[Towill] Maui right behind us.

1253
01:20:54,379 --> 01:20:56,813
Very, very excited to be back home.

1254
01:20:56,848 --> 01:20:59,476
Been 11 days of just seeing the horizon,

1255
01:20:59,517 --> 01:21:02,008
we're finally seeing the islands.

1256
01:21:03,321 --> 01:21:06,188
And... I...

1257
01:21:06,224 --> 01:21:08,692
...really have a lot to say,
and I just can't say it.

1258
01:21:08,726 --> 01:21:10,284
Um...

1259
01:21:25,076 --> 01:21:26,668
Whoo!

1260
01:21:26,711 --> 01:21:29,179
[Welch] A little happy
little Turtle up there.

1261
01:21:29,214 --> 01:21:31,580
[Van Os] Break out the inscription tool!

1262
01:21:31,616 --> 01:21:33,516
[Fielding] Spike yourself away!

1263
01:21:33,551 --> 01:21:34,984
[Kane] I'm lovin' this!

1264
01:21:52,737 --> 01:21:55,706
[Wilmot] So here we are,
we're in the famous Molokai Channel.

1265
01:21:55,740 --> 01:21:58,470
It feels really good to be here.

1266
01:21:58,510 --> 01:22:01,877
We, uh... we don't really know
where our competitors are,

1267
01:22:01,913 --> 01:22:06,145
'cause all the tracking devices
are lost or malfunctioning.

1268
01:22:06,184 --> 01:22:11,622
So we're sort of coming down here with
our eyes closed on our competitors.

1269
01:22:11,656 --> 01:22:13,886
[Sanderson] One thing these guys
are gonna have to be conscious of

1270
01:22:13,925 --> 01:22:16,018
is what we call "channel fever."

1271
01:22:16,060 --> 01:22:19,154
There's a good chance
that they'll be a little over-tired

1272
01:22:19,197 --> 01:22:22,394
and a little overexcited and they'll
starting to be thinking about...

1273
01:22:22,433 --> 01:22:24,458
Uh, about hitting the dock.

1274
01:22:25,203 --> 01:22:27,068
[Will] I'm excited to see my family.

1275
01:22:27,105 --> 01:22:32,304
All I wanna do is go to Oahu.
I just wanna get to Honolulu.

1276
01:22:32,343 --> 01:22:35,835
Dude, I want mai tais.
Would anybody like an espresso?

1277
01:22:35,880 --> 01:22:40,078
- [laughs]
- I'm making some downstairs.

1278
01:22:40,118 --> 01:22:43,383
[Sanderson] This race has been won
and lost on the last day before.

1279
01:22:43,421 --> 01:22:45,616
[Wilmot] You know what's really
interesting right now?

1280
01:22:45,657 --> 01:22:47,181
I'm coming down to the finish

1281
01:22:47,225 --> 01:22:50,991
and I have planned for nothing
after this finish.

1282
01:22:51,029 --> 01:22:53,793
This finish has been
my, like, whole year,

1283
01:22:53,831 --> 01:22:56,095
like, my whole life up to this point.

1284
01:23:01,372 --> 01:23:04,739
- [crowd cheering]
- [horns blaring]

1285
01:23:05,777 --> 01:23:09,474
<i>[man] Aloha,</i> Samba Pa Ti!

1286
01:23:09,514 --> 01:23:11,277
<i>Transpac Yacht Club</i>
<i>welcomes you</i>

1287
01:23:11,316 --> 01:23:14,877
<i>and congratulates you</i>
<i>on your successful race.</i>

1288
01:23:14,919 --> 01:23:16,580
I'm sure Mr. Kilroy thought that,

1289
01:23:16,621 --> 01:23:20,887
he had a superior crew, superior boat,
and would beat them handily.

1290
01:23:20,925 --> 01:23:23,416
But, that's not the way it came out.

1291
01:23:23,461 --> 01:23:25,827
[Kilroy] It was just give
and take for quite a while.

1292
01:23:25,863 --> 01:23:28,889
I think it was Robbie Naismith
saying, "Come on, guys.

1293
01:23:28,933 --> 01:23:32,425
We can't let these kids beat us. We
couldn't live with that on our résumé."

1294
01:23:32,470 --> 01:23:34,495
You know, saying it kiddingly,
but, yeah,

1295
01:23:34,539 --> 01:23:36,530
you know, that's just sailboat racing.

1296
01:23:36,574 --> 01:23:38,166
Yeah!

1297
01:23:41,245 --> 01:23:43,213
<i>[man] Diamond Head control,</i>
<i>Diamond Head control,</i>

1298
01:23:43,247 --> 01:23:44,509
<i>This is Diamond Head Light.</i>

1299
01:23:44,549 --> 01:23:47,643
Samba Pa Ti <i>crossed the line at 0156.</i>

1300
01:23:47,685 --> 01:23:50,518
<i>Congratulations,</i> Samba Pa Ti.

1301
01:23:50,555 --> 01:23:52,716
[Wilmot] It's sort
of mind-blowing for me.

1302
01:23:52,757 --> 01:23:55,351
I just take it all in, especially now,

1303
01:23:55,393 --> 01:23:56,985
ten miles from the finish line.

1304
01:23:57,028 --> 01:23:59,258
You, uh... you can't
really contemplate it.

1305
01:24:02,567 --> 01:24:04,000
It's pretty heavy.

1306
01:24:07,505 --> 01:24:12,067
Now I'm gonna go steer my boat home
for the last time ever.

1307
01:24:47,545 --> 01:24:49,843
[sounding horn]

1308
01:24:49,881 --> 01:24:53,373
[Wilmot] Keep trimming, Towiller.
Not there yet, mate.

1309
01:24:56,254 --> 01:24:58,245
- [Branning] Pull string in.
- [Wilmot] Pull!

1310
01:24:58,289 --> 01:25:00,120
- It's there.
- [Tulloch] Red buoy!

1311
01:25:00,158 --> 01:25:03,992
See that red buoy? You were a dinghy
sailor before, weren't you?

1312
01:25:04,028 --> 01:25:08,590
- It's there. [laughs]
- Oh!

1313
01:25:15,773 --> 01:25:17,934
- [Fielding] You ready?
- [Van Os] Ready.

1314
01:25:22,146 --> 01:25:25,172
[Towill] Wow, this is gonna be sick!

1315
01:25:34,926 --> 01:25:36,291
[Wilmot] Here we go, home!

1316
01:25:36,327 --> 01:25:38,795
- [bell clanging]
- Oh! We made it!

1317
01:25:38,830 --> 01:25:40,263
Not yet, not yet.

1318
01:25:43,000 --> 01:25:46,026
- [foghorn blaring]
- [cheering]

1319
01:26:25,376 --> 01:26:27,003
[man] Nice work, you guys.

1320
01:26:27,044 --> 01:26:30,571
- [Kane] Yes, we're home! Yeah, buddy!
- Whoo!

1321
01:26:39,791 --> 01:26:41,884
[crowd cheering]

1322
01:26:41,926 --> 01:26:45,157
<i>[man] Aloha,</i> Morning Light!

1323
01:26:45,696 --> 01:26:48,164
<i>Transpac Yacht Club</i>
<i>welcomes you to Honolulu</i>

1324
01:26:48,199 --> 01:26:51,100
<i>and congratulates you</i>
<i>on your successful race.</i>

1325
01:26:56,240 --> 01:26:58,470
[Disney] When I did
this thing the first time,

1326
01:26:58,509 --> 01:27:00,500
it changed me for the rest of my life,

1327
01:27:00,545 --> 01:27:02,877
but I don't think
I knew that at the time.

1328
01:27:02,914 --> 01:27:05,348
I think it kind of
comes to you later on.

1329
01:27:07,952 --> 01:27:10,284
You have a resource
that you can look back on

1330
01:27:10,321 --> 01:27:14,451
and say, "I dealt with life and I dealt
with it well and gracefully."

1331
01:27:14,492 --> 01:27:16,722
That's what it really means in the end.

1332
01:27:16,761 --> 01:27:18,956
It's about the journey.

1333
01:27:26,771 --> 01:27:29,001
<i>[Fielding]</i>
<i>This is gonna be an epic story.</i>

1334
01:27:31,242 --> 01:27:33,540
<i>This is gonna be our first story.</i>

1335
01:27:35,780 --> 01:27:38,180
<i>This is gonna be probably</i>
<i>our favorite story.</i>

1336
01:27:39,183 --> 01:27:40,650
<i>How it all began.</i>

1337
01:27:57,935 --> 01:28:00,426
[crowd cheering]

1338
01:28:04,609 --> 01:28:07,544
[Wilmot] Here we are, day 14
of the <i>Morning Light</i> adventure,

1339
01:28:07,578 --> 01:28:09,546
except this time, we're on land.

1340
01:28:09,580 --> 01:28:12,140
Finally, believe it or not, we're here.

1341
01:28:12,183 --> 01:28:14,549
Wow. It's, uh...

1342
01:28:16,354 --> 01:28:18,914
Yeah. I'm not gonna be
able to, uh...

1343
01:28:18,956 --> 01:28:22,323
I don't think I could find a team
like this ever again, so...

1344
01:28:24,228 --> 01:28:28,722
...it's, uh... [inhales] Yeah, it's...

1345
01:28:28,766 --> 01:28:31,997
It's emotional. These guys are...

1346
01:28:32,036 --> 01:28:33,469
Hang on.

1347
01:28:48,119 --> 01:28:50,019
Yeah.
I need a minute.

1348
01:29:00,731 --> 01:29:05,293
Sad! Oh, I'm so sad.

1349
01:29:05,336 --> 01:29:08,169
Yeah. [groans]

1350
01:29:11,142 --> 01:29:13,303
Wow.

1351
01:29:13,344 --> 01:29:15,369
If they put this
in the film, I'll kill 'em.

1352
01:29:15,413 --> 01:29:18,109
- Of course it's going in.
- Yeah. [sniffles]

1353
01:29:18,149 --> 01:29:20,413
I was just telling Robbie,
I was like, you know,

1354
01:29:20,451 --> 01:29:23,716
I thought I was gonna be all broken up
and upset when you're leavin',

1355
01:29:23,754 --> 01:29:26,382
but... I'm gonna see all you
guys again in like a month

1356
01:29:26,424 --> 01:29:28,255
and like, constantly after that.

1357
01:29:28,292 --> 01:29:30,658
- I'm not worried about it at all.
- [Wilmot] Yeah.

1358
01:29:30,695 --> 01:29:32,925
Once again, BZ to the rescue.

1359
01:29:32,964 --> 01:29:37,060
Just a sign-off to my team.
Last day as skipper.

1360
01:29:39,036 --> 01:29:41,266
Last day, uh, steering my boat,

1361
01:29:42,773 --> 01:29:44,900
and, uh, let's go for a ride.

1362
01:29:46,310 --> 01:29:50,212
OK, boys! Let's go.
One last time.

1363
01:29:50,247 --> 01:29:52,010
Together.

1364
01:29:57,855 --> 01:30:01,552
<i>[Tulloch] When the race was over,</i>
<i>it basically was over for us.</i>

1365
01:30:01,592 --> 01:30:03,583
<i>We had spent so long with each other</i>

1366
01:30:03,627 --> 01:30:06,425
<i>and the finish was what we had</i>
<i>always dreamed of and hoped for</i>

1367
01:30:06,464 --> 01:30:09,399
<i>and wished for and then</i>
<i>we crossed the finish line,</i>

1368
01:30:09,433 --> 01:30:13,369
<i>and it was like, "What next?</i>
<i>Wh-Where do we go from here?"</i>

1369
01:30:24,215 --> 01:30:28,117
<i>[Schubert] The best thing was just</i>
<i>this sense of accomplishment at the end.</i>

1370
01:30:28,152 --> 01:30:31,519
<i>If we had won the race we would have</i>
<i>thought that the Transpac was easy.</i>

1371
01:30:31,555 --> 01:30:33,250
<i>You have to respect that race a lot.</i>

1372
01:30:33,290 --> 01:30:35,622
<i>It's a long distance and a lot goes on.</i>

1373
01:30:43,067 --> 01:30:45,627
<i>[Towill] The biggest thing</i>
<i>I learned from the project</i>

1374
01:30:45,669 --> 01:30:49,571
<i>has just been the real value in teamwork</i>
<i>and how special it is</i>

1375
01:30:49,607 --> 01:30:52,474
<i>when 15 people can come together</i>
<i>and accomplish something</i>

1376
01:30:52,510 --> 01:30:55,604
<i>that no one of us</i>
<i>could have done on our own.</i>

1377
01:31:07,291 --> 01:31:10,089
<i>The days you go out</i>
<i>and everything goes the way you planned</i>

1378
01:31:10,127 --> 01:31:12,152
<i>and everything goes perfectly,</i>
<i>you learn nothing from.</i>

1379
01:31:12,196 --> 01:31:14,130
<i>It's the days you go out</i>
<i>then everything falls apart,</i>

1380
01:31:14,165 --> 01:31:15,689
<i>that's when you learn the most.</i>

1381
01:31:15,733 --> 01:31:19,032
<i>And I really learned that</i>
<i>in a very literal way on</i> Morning Light

1382
01:31:19,070 --> 01:31:21,470
<i>and really kind of changed</i>
<i>my whole outlook on life.</i>

1383
01:31:27,845 --> 01:31:29,506
<i>[Kane] You realize</i>
<i>what's important to you.</i>

1384
01:31:29,547 --> 01:31:33,176
<i>To be able to pack my whole life</i>
<i>in a small bag for ten days,</i>

1385
01:31:33,217 --> 01:31:35,515
<i>just those things</i>
<i>and being on the ocean,</i>

1386
01:31:35,553 --> 01:31:37,987
<i>was probably the happiest</i>
<i>ten days of my life.</i>

1387
01:31:48,866 --> 01:31:51,198
<i>[Branning] Being on an ocean</i>
<i>is about as close</i>

1388
01:31:51,235 --> 01:31:54,398
<i>as you can put together</i>
<i>peace and fear.</i>

1389
01:31:55,773 --> 01:31:59,539
<i>It's absolutely peaceful</i>
<i>and it's just so beautiful...</i>

1390
01:31:59,577 --> 01:32:01,807
<i>... but, man,</i>
<i>it can go bad pretty quickly.</i>

1391
01:32:01,846 --> 01:32:05,009
<i>I think we were about as well prepared</i>
<i>as we could be for anything.</i>

1392
01:32:19,330 --> 01:32:22,026
<i>[Manson] You...</i>
<i>You realize, out on the ocean,</i>

1393
01:32:22,066 --> 01:32:25,968
<i>it's... it's a different type of life,</i>
<i>and it gives you a new respect.</i>

1394
01:32:26,003 --> 01:32:28,494
<i>Kind of hard to explain.</i>
<i>It's like you feel in power,</i>

1395
01:32:28,539 --> 01:32:30,166
<i>like you've conquered somethin'</i>

1396
01:32:30,207 --> 01:32:33,643
<i>that you know a lot of people</i>
<i>haven't had the chance to do.</i>

1397
01:32:33,677 --> 01:32:36,043
<i>You feel very fortunate</i>
<i>at the same time.</i>

1398
01:32:48,259 --> 01:32:50,352
<i>[Wilmot] Pretty much what</i>
Morning Light <i>did for me</i>

1399
01:32:50,394 --> 01:32:52,988
<i>is it opened a lot</i>
<i>of boundaries that I had.</i>

1400
01:32:53,030 --> 01:32:57,467
<i>My grades have improved at college,</i>
<i>my work has improved on land</i>

1401
01:32:57,501 --> 01:32:59,935
<i>and now I feel like</i>
<i>I can just get out there</i>

1402
01:32:59,970 --> 01:33:02,632
<i>and anything that I apply myself,</i>
<i>I can do.</i>

1403
01:33:13,617 --> 01:33:15,949
<i>[Fielding] You know,</i>
<i>whenever I see my teammates,</i>

1404
01:33:15,986 --> 01:33:18,318
<i>they'll always be</i>
<i>these special people to me.</i>

1405
01:33:18,355 --> 01:33:20,346
<i>We could be in the middle</i>
<i>of New York City,</i>

1406
01:33:20,391 --> 01:33:23,189
<i>we could be in Shanghai,</i>
<i>we could be hikin' on a mountain,</i>

1407
01:33:23,227 --> 01:33:27,027
<i>and we're still gonna have a connection</i>
<i>that no one else around us shares,</i>

1408
01:33:27,064 --> 01:33:29,225
<i>and that's a special feeling.</i>

1409
01:33:35,506 --> 01:33:37,872
<i>[# Long Time Coming]</i>

1410
01:37:47,324 --> 01:37:49,815
[cheers]

1411
01:37:49,860 --> 01:37:51,623
[laugh] Take two!

